{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"484cd016-f663-4e57-84b6-a20c938c144c","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I can't inspect it directly. Here's how to determine the runtime and configure dumps on your target system:\n\n## 1. Identify the Runtime\n\n```bash\n# CoreCLR loads libcoreclr.so; NativeAOT does not\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -q libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Alternative: check for JIT library (only CoreCLR has it)\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -q libclrjit && echo \"CoreCLR (JIT present)\"\n```\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### For CoreCLR:\n\nSet these **environment variables** before launching the app:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1          # enable crash dumps\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4            # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\nAlso ensure the OS core dump limit is set:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\n### For NativeAOT:\n\nNativeAOT doesn't use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` variables. Rely on **OS-level core dumps** instead:\n\n```bash\n# Set core dump size limit\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# Configure core pattern (requires root)\necho '/tmp/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\nOptionally install and use **systemd-coredump** for managed collection:\n\n```bash\n# Check if already active\ncat /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n# If it shows \"|/lib/systemd/systemd-coredump\", it's already set up\n# View dumps with: coredumpctl list\n```\n\n## 3. Analysis Tools\n\n| Runtime | Tool | Command |\n|---------|------|---------|\n| CoreCLR | `dotnet-dump` | `dotnet-dump analyze /tmp/dumps/coredump.*` |\n| NativeAOT | `lldb` / `gdb` | `lldb --core /tmp/dumps/core.*` |\n| Both | `createdump` | Ships with CoreCLR at `$DOTNET_ROOT/shared/Microsoft.NETCore.App/*/createdump` |\n\n**Quick summary:** If `libcoreclr.so` appears in `/proc/<pid>/maps`, it's CoreCLR — use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` env vars. Otherwise it's NativeAOT — use OS-level `core_pattern`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7f59a482-ab04-4818-9b29-023692211c2b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine (PID 12345 is not running here). That makes sense — the user is asking for guidance, not necessarily running the app on this exact machine. Let me give them practical instructions instead.","outputTokens":763,"requestId":"F887:16BC0E:535AFC3:5BB3487:69FA0094"},"id":"57e46895-e189-402b-8e25-377c0f372c3e","timestamp":"2026-05-05T14:37:30.657Z","parentId":"12fbaf16-c29b-4cde-87e8-574be4bd83b2"}
